20) install virtual enviorment manager for python - virtualenv
	
	https://www.quora.com/What-is-the-difference-between-python-virtualenv-and-a-conda-environment
	"
	Conda environments are essentially a replacement for virtualenv. Both conda environments and virtualenv are aimed at creating an “environment” with isolated package installs. 
	They aim to solve the problem of having multiple python projects on the same system with conflicting package requirements. 
	If you have project A that requires tensorflow-1.8 and project B that uses tensorflow-1.9,
	these environments allow you to have the right version installed for each project.

	The main difference between the two is that conda is a bit more full featured/”magic”. 
	Conda has dedicated syntax for creating environments and installing packages, and can also manage installing different versions of python too. 
	For virtualenv, you just activate the environment and then use all the normal commands.

	For example, for conda the command for a new environment named “myenv” using python 3.4, scipy version 0.15.0, and packages astroid and babel of any version:
	
	$conda create -n myenv python=3.4 scipy=0.15.0 astroid babel 
	
	In virtualenv:

	<manually install python 3.4 however your system installs it> 
	$ virtualenv --python=/usr/bin/python3.4 myenv 
	$ source myenv/bin/activate 
	$ pip install scipy==0.15.0 
	$ pip install astroid 
	$ pip install babel 
	"

	https://deeplearning.lipingyang.org/2018/12/23/anaconda-vs-miniconda-vs-virtualenv/
	"
	Some context: Pip is a package manager, and virtualenv is an environment manager; and conda is both.
	Specifically, conda is a packaging tool and installer that aims to do more than what pip does; it handles library dependencies outside of the Python packages as well as the Python packages themselves. 		Conda also creates a virtual environment, like virtualenv does.
	Choose Virtualenv only when you have sudo access to the machine you are working on. 
	It is much easier to setup conda rather than virtualenv for a regular (i.e., non sudo/root) user on a linux/Mac machine.
	"

	We will install virtualenv as we want less things to confine us. 
	I also read somehere that packages that are installed with pip are different from those installed with conda, and so this may cause problems down the line when some package is only configured for pip.
	

	a) Installing virtualenv - installation is through python 3, but we can also create enviorments in python2
		https://tech.serhatteker.com/post/2018-12/virtualenv/
		
		$ sudo apt-get install python3-pip
		$ sudo pip3 install virtualenv


	b) testing with PythonRobotics
		
		$ cd
		$ cd repos
		$ git clone https://github.com/AtsushiSakai/PythonRobotics
		$ cd PythonRobotics
		$ python3 -m venv env #this will create a folder called env which will hold all the packages and the such. It is recommended to put it under git ignore. DONT USE THIS METHOD. CALL VIRTUALENV TO CREATE VIRTUAL ENVIORMENT, NOT PYTHON.
		$ source env/bin/activate %activate the enviorment
		$ which python #confirm location of python interpreter:
		$ pip3 install -r requirements.txt #installing packages from requirements.txt
		!!! This failed because PythonRobotics was written in Python2 and we created an enviorment in Python3! (This was later discovered to be completely wrong)

		a) deactivate the current enviorment -> $deactivate
		b) delete the env folder
		c) create a new python2 enviorment, this time in a hidden folder -> $ virtualenv -p /usr/bin/python2.7 .venv
		d) source the new enviorment -> $ source .venv/bin/activate
		e) install the requirements -> $ pip install -r requirements.txt
		!!! This also failed for some reason... I just installed the packages writen in requirements.txt manually
		$pip install numpy
		$pip install scipy
		...
		finally the last one had a problem, $pip install cvxpy -> ERROR: Could not build wheels for osqp which use PEP 517 and cannot be installed directly
		to view list of packages insatlled on our env -> $pip list --local
		!!! I opened the PythonRobotics README.md and noticed that they do require python 3.9... Trying with python 3 again! (deleting .venv after deactivating)


		-> discovered that cvxpy requires python>3.7 and I was using 3.6.9
		
		Installing python 3.9
		from https://askubuntu.com/questions/1318846/how-do-i-install-python-3-9:
		$ sudo apt update
		$ sudo apt install software-properties-common
		$ sudo add-apt-repository ppa:deadsnakes/ppa 
		$ sudo apt update
		$ sudo apt install python3.9
		$ python3.9 --version -> Python 3.9.x

		$ virtualenv -p /usr/bin/python3.9 .venv
		$ source .venv/bin/activate
		
		I noticed pip3 install faills... 
		I looked into the default version of python the system which was running was python 2.7
		To verify: open a new terminal, and write $python --version
		To Change default: $ alias python=python3.9 (this will be needed on every new terminal, unless inserted into .bashrc)
		-> this also failed

		I tried this command:
	 		$ sudo apt install python3.9-distutils 
		following advice from https://stackoverflow.com/questions/55749206/modulenotfounderror-no-module-named-distutils-core
		It solved pip3 install, but this still fails.
		
		Finaly, I installed the dev package for python 3.9 using:
			$ sudo apt-get install python3.x-dev
		Following advice from https://stackoverflow.com/questions/26053982/setup-script-exited-with-error-command-x86-64-linux-gnu-gcc-failed-with-exit.
		This worked!
	
		To configure vs code to work with virtual enviorments, I read https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/python/environments:
			a) open the search bar with cntrl+shift+p
			b) seach "Python: Select Interpreter"
			c) add/select the interpeter from .venv

		Note: my virtual enviorment size with ~300MB. If im planning on having lots of projects, I might aswell learn to use virtualenvwrapper. 

		another good read for command and such: https://packaging.python.org/guides/installing-using-pip-and-virtual-environments/

