26) How to set up my Monitor at the lab:
	https://askubuntu.com/questions/393400/is-it-possible-to-have-different-dpi-configurations-for-two-different-screens

	$ xrandr --output eDP-1 --primary --mode 3840x2160 --scale 1x1 --rotate normal
	$ xrandr --output DP-1-2 --mode 1920x1080 --scale 2x2 --pos 3840x1080 --rotate normal

	$ sudo apt install arandr -> run arandr to confirm monitor locations
	had some error "Gtk-Message: Failed to load module "canberra-gtk-module"
			$ sudo apt-get install libcanberra-gtk-module:i386
			$ sudo apt install libcanberra-gtk-module libcanberra-gtk3-module
	from https://askubuntu.com/questions/342202/failed-to-load-module-canberra-gtk-module-but-already-installed
	-> second one did the trick

	did this aswell :https://askubuntu.com/questions/6137/saving-monitor-settings  -------- NOT SURE IF ANY GOOD, REMOVED INSTALLED ITEMS OF THIS
	$ sudo wget -O /usr/local/sbin/update-monitor-position https://raw.githubusercontent.com/NicolasBernaerts/ubuntu-scripts/master/ubuntugnome/update-monitor-position
	$ sudo chmod +x /usr/local/sbin/update-monitor-position
	$ sudo wget -O /usr/share/applications/update-monitor-position.desktop https://raw.githubusercontent.com/NicolasBernaerts/ubuntu-scripts/master/ubuntugnome/update-monitor-position.desktop
	$ sudo chmod +x /usr/share/applications/update-monitor-position.desktop

	SOLUTION: (email I wrote mark)
	After writing you the email I figured it must be the usb-c to HDMI. It worked perfectly in the past when connecting to a TV, but this is a 		monitor after-all.
	I know it has an internal chip that converts DP data to HDMI data as the usb-c outputs DP.
	I figured it must be some kind of an initialization function that is missed when the stars don't align (or in my case, some frequency).
	Two solutions:
	1) place a command to disconnect and reconnect the monitor on a loop, until initialization occurred.
	2) switch to a usb-c to DP cable. 
	
	
