32) Backing up my system - NOT USED ANYMORE. I USE THE "deja dup" back utility which is the default one for ubuntu. it's listed as Backups with a safe icon
	guide - https://ubuntuforums.org/showthread.php?t=35087: ALSO CONTAINS THE INSTRUCTIONS FOR RESTORING

	What should I use to backup my system then?" might you ask. Easy; the same thing you use to backup/compress everything else; TAR. Unlike Windows, Linux doesn't restrict root access to anything, so you can just throw every single file on a partition in a TAR file!

	$ sudo su
	$ cd /
	
	$ tar cvpzf backup.tgz --exclude=/proc --exclude=/lost+found --exclude=/backup.tgz --exclude=/mnt --exclude=/sys /
	OR 
	$ tar cvpjf backup.tar.bz2 --exclude=/proc --exclude=/lost+found --exclude=/backup.tar.bz2 --exclude=/mnt --exclude=/sys /
	

	Restoration:
	$ tar xvpfz backup.tgz -C /
	OR
	$ tar xvpfj backup.tar.bz2 -C /

	$ mkdir proc
	$ mkdir lost+found
	$ mkdir mnt
	$ mkdir sys
	etc...

	$ sudo reboot
	
	
	$ tar -cvpzf /backup.tar.gz --exclude=/backup.tar.gz --one-file-system /

	
	a little different: https://askubuntu.com/questions/7809/how-to-back-up-my-entire-system
	'''
	To restore your files when the system goes pear-shaped, use a Live CD. Mount the bad system under /media or /mnt and then run tar xf /path/to/drive/with/backup.tar.gz -C /mnt (or /media).
	'''

