34) number (33) was a failure, but we want to make location bar default in nautilus
	a) aprrently just by pressing 'ctrl+L' will show the location bar in a text way.
	
	b) from https://www.omgubuntu.co.uk/2011/11/how-to-set-location-bar-in-nautilus-as-default
	$ sudo apt update 
	$ sudo apt install dconf-editor -y
	open dconf Editor program via "show applications" that can be found in bottom left
	then change "Always use location entry" in org>gnome>nautilus>preferences
	
	OR
	
	$ gsettings set org.gnome.nautilus.preferences always-use-location-entry true

	Note: Sometimes when asked by ubuntu to pin point a file a special menu will show up that will ask the user to navigate.
		this does not set this menu location entry to true, but 'ctrl+L' trick stil works

35) creating my own bash commands!
	with the help of https://medium.com/devnetwork/how-to-create-your-own-custom-terminal-commands-c5008782a78e

	a) creating the file where the commands are stored 
	$ cd ~
	$ touch .my_custom_commands.sh
	$ chmod +x .my_custom_commands.sh
	$ gedit .my_custom_commands.sh
	
	copy the following to the file:	
	#!/bin/bash
	
	# prints the input
	function print_my_input() {
	  echo 'Your input: ' $1
	}

	add 'source ~/.my_custom_commands.sh' to ~/.bashrc 
	this can be done manually or by the following command $ echo "source ~/.my_custom_commands.sh" >> ~/.bashrc 

	open a new terminal, then try $ print_my_input 'test'
	
	b) open nautilus in pwd
	function nautilus_here() {
		nautilus "$pwd"	
	}

	c) change terminal path of linke'd folder to real folder
	function link2real() {
		cd $(pwd -P)
	}

