	https://askubuntu.com/questions/883244/after-compiling-bluez-5-43-from-source-bluetooth-v-still-returns-5-41
	points out that bluetoohd may be found in /usr/local/libexec/bluetooth and needs to be symlinked to /usr/local/bin

	$ sudo ln -s /usr/local/libexec/bluetooth/bluetoothd /usr/local/bin/bluetoothd

	in https://askubuntu.com/questions/1139404/sony-noise-cancelling-headphones-wh-1000xm2-3-and-bluetooth-initial-autoconnec
	it was suggested to run "$ systemctl daemon-reload" after the sudo make install.
	'''
	be executed. This will delete the previous configuration created by generators, re-run all generators, and cause systemd to reload units from disk.
	'''
	it also suggeested to run
	$ sudo service bluetooth restart #this failed

	https://unix.stackexchange.com/questions/608116/bluetooth-wont-turn-on-on-ubuntu-20-04
	https://askubuntu.com/questions/804946/systemctl-how-to-unmask

	$ systemctl unmask bluetooth.service
	$ sudo systemctl enable bluetooth
	$ sudo systemctl start bluetooth
	$ sudo service bluetooth restart #will work

	$ sudo apt install blueman -> reveals more information
	#somthing about installation paths still seems problematic

	This tell us how to use the --prefix argument in the ./configure	
	https://askubuntu.com/questions/891835/what-does-prefix-do-exactly-when-used-in-configure
	https://raspberrypi.stackexchange.com/questions/66540/installing-bluez-5-44-onto-raspbian

	$ sudo apt install bluez
	$ whereis bluetoothd --> bluetoothd: /usr/sbin/bluetoothd /usr/share/man/man8/bluetoothd.8 /usr/share/man/man8/bluetoothd.8.g
	$ cd ~/Downloads/bluez-5.52
	$ ./configure --prefix=/usr --mandir=/usr/share/man --sysconfdir=/etc --localstatedir=/var --enable-experimental
	$ make
	$ sudo checkinstall
	$ sudo ln -s /usr/libexec/bluetooth/bluetoothd /usr/lib/bluetooth/bluetoothd #these links won't be removed with '$ sudo apt remove bluez'
	$ sudo ln -s /usr/local/libexec/bluetooth/bluetoothd /usr/local/bin/bluetoothd
	$ sudo apt install pulseaudio-module-bluetooth	
	$ killall pulseaudio
	$ sudo systemctl daemon-reload

	
	# returning things to how they were
	$ sudo apt purge bluez
	$ sudo rm /usr/lib/bluetooth/bluetoothd
	$ sudo rm /usr/local/bin/bluetoothd
	$ sudo apt install bluez #version 5.48
	$ sudo apt install pulseaudio-module-bluetooth	
	$ killall pulseaudio
	$ sudo systemctl daemon-reload

48) install cmake version 3.22 WITHOUT REMOVING THE DEFAULT 3.10
	When upgrading we can remove and then install the new version, but removing cmake 3.10 will also remove critical ROS files which will break the ROS installation. 
	We will install cmake 3.12 localy and call on it when we want!
	https://answers.ros.org/question/293119/how-can-i-updateremove-cmake-without-partially-deleting-my-ros-distribution/

	$ cd ~/Downloads
	$ wget https://github.com/Kitware/CMake/releases/download/v3.22.0-rc1/cmake-3.22.0-rc1.tar.gz #the link was manually obtained from https://cmake.org/download/
	$ tar -xf cmake-3.22.0-rc1.tar.gz
	$ cd cmake-3.22.0-rc1/
	$ ./bootstrap --prefix=$HOME/LocalInstalls/cmake-install
	$ make
	$ make install

	#These two export lines make sure your using the updated cmake and not the system one:
	$ export PATH=$HOME/LocalInstalls/cmake-install/bin:$PATH
	$ export CMAKE_PREFIX_PATH=$HOME/LocalInstalls/cmake-install:$CMAKE_PREFIX_PATH

Notes on "sudo make install" vs "make install" from https://unix.stackexchange.com/questions/20953/difference-between-make-install-and-sudo-make-install
	'''
	As has been answered above, sudo make install lets you install the files in directories which are otherwise read-only to you as a user.

	The problem I can foresee is that at a later date you may want to uninstall or upgrade the program. If you still have the source code directory tree then a make uninstall will uninstall the program for you but if, as many other typical users, you had deleted the source code directory tree then you are out of luck. And since you have not installed the program using a package management system, you may also be unable to uninstall the program that way.

	The best way to install such programs may be to install them in your home directory. Pass the option --prefix=/home/<user>/<some>/<directory> to ./configure. This will allow you to use make install instead of sudo make install since /home/<user>/<some>/<directory> is writable by you. Also uninstallation is a snap -- rm -rf /home/<user>/<some>/<directory>
	'''

